Scotland's independent schools have an academically successful history, and in 2018, this success was sustained by outstanding test results, supported by sports, art, music, and other civil society studies.
With over 30,000 students in Scotland and represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), these schools work to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their later education and higher education, their chosen career, and becoming world citizens.
As educational institutions that can prepare and implement a special curriculum for students, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and essential course in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to someone in the language he understands,
If you speak native language, you will be addressing your heart."
If we want to connect with people from other countries and build mutual trust, this promise is a strong reminder that we should not rely solely on English.
Based on this year's final exam results, we can see that language classes in independent schools are at the top of the scoreboards with the highest passing grade rates.
This year, a total of 68% of students taking foreign language courses passed their courses with A, a high grade.
According to data collected from SCIS' 74 member schools, 72 percent of students taking Chinese courses, 72 percent of those taking German, 69 percent of those taking French, and 63 percent of those taking Spanish passed their courses with A.
These data show that independent schools in Scotland support foreign language courses as essential skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Language courses, which are elective courses, are now valued in the curricula of independent schools and other schools with FeTeMM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics) courses.
A 2014 study by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17% of the reasons employers have trouble getting new employees into vacant positions is related to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming even more imperative in preparing young people for their future careers.
These skills have been essential skills in the globalizing world, as more employers are required to know the language for possible job opportunities.
If a person knows a second language regardless of his or her chosen career, he or she will have a real advantage in the future because he or she has this skill that he or she can use for life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from outside countries spontaneously puts more than one multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov, 75% of the more than 4,000 people living in the United Kingdom do not speak enough foreign languages to converse, and with the exception of French (15%) in no foreign language, the proportion of people who speak the language does not reach a two-digit number.
Therefore, investing in language learning from today is of great importance to the children of the future.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will increase the chances of children finding a suitable and reasonable job for them in the future.
The languages taught in schools in Scotland vary.
Certain schools offer more traditional modern language options, while some schools also teach languages that are thought to be important for the United Kingdom in 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Your child may choose one of the various foreign language options taught by expert teachers in this field in independent schools, no matter what field he or she is interested in.
Scottish independent schools aim to provide a teaching environment that will prepare children for the future and equip them with the skills necessary for success.
In today's global business environment, it is an unmistakable fact that foreign languages continue to be vital to the country's future, which must also be reflected in real educational life.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and success to young people of Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
