The North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing embargoes in the country deepened mistrust of the United States, and under these circumstances the country could not unilaterally relinquish its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the world establishment's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and promising that it would not produce nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"Despite this, we don't see the return from the United States," he added.
"Without any confidence in the United States, we will not be able to have faith in our own national security, and under these circumstances we will have no way to unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
Ri rephrases the familiar North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance against a "staged" approach that North Korea will be rewarded for taking gradual steps, while his statements seem important because he unilaterally did not reject the removal of nuclear weapons as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri made a reference to joint statements by Donald Trump and Kim Jong Un at a summit between the incumbent U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, where Kim pledged to work towards "nuclear denuclearization of the Korean peninsula".
North Korea is looking for ways to formally end the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington was also resisting calls to loosen tough international sanctions in North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'first denuclearization' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its objectives in compelling ways, even opposing 'war being declared to be over'," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is the empty dream of people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the ongoing sanctions reinforce our insecurity."
Ri made no hint of a second summit plan between US leader Trump and Kim, which was highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he emphasized three talks between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If this issue of denuclearization had been addressed by South Korea and not the United States, the issue of denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have been this blind knot."
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech was quite different from last year's speech at the UN General Assembly last year, when "Mr. Devil President" Trump said it was inevitable that North Korea's rockets would target the U.S. mainland after Kim called him a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea last year, praised Kim at the United Nations this year for having the courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said there is still much work to be done and sanctions should continue until North Korea is free of nuclear.
On Wednesday, Trump said, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years, or five months," there is no time frame for that.
