Harvard students take enough rest classes
This year at Harvard University, a new course leads all of its students to sleep more in order to combat the growing macho culture of 'all-nighters' studying through caffeine.
One academic found that students of the world's number one university were unaware of even the most basic information when it came to taking care of themselves.
In the United States, Charles Czeisler, a Harvard Medical School sleep treatment professor and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believed was the first of its kind.
He drew inspiration from a speech he gave about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning ability.
"At the end of the conversation, a female student came to me and said, 'Why is all this being said to me now, when I'm in my senior year?'"
He said that no one has ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much."
Opened for the first time this year, the course explains the basics of how good sleep habits help students achieve academic and athletic performance, and also improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general manager of health care at the university, said the university decided to open the course after realizing that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course contains a series of interactive tasks.
One chapter includes a dorm room picture where students listen to the effects of coffee and light by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, instructors and books and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of regular sleep.
In another episode, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase their risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their own daily routines.
"We know that students will not change their behavior instantly.
However, we believe that if you have the right to learn how to choose to smoke, they have the right to learn the same way," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of "working all night" still exists, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students, namely sleep deprivation, is a growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and ensuring that sleep is of good quality should be the "secret weapon" for students to struggle with stress, fatigue and anxiety, even to avoid gaining too much weight, because sleep deprivation causes students to feel hungry all the time as the brain puts them into starvation mode, he said.
Raymond So, who studied chemical and physical biology from California at the age of 19, took a class of Professor Czeisler in his first year at school last year, and assisted Professor Czeisler in designing the course.
He said the lesson opened his eyes and inspired him to create campus-wide awareness.
In the next step, he hopes to ask his graduate students to complete a similar course before joining competitive institutions.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm to the time they will wake up, as well as to the time they will sleep, and warns them of the harmful effects of "blue light", which disrupts the daily rhythm emitted from electronic displays and LED lights, causing problems of falling asleep.
