World Wide Web's Inventor Plans to Launch a New Internet Project to Compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, is starting a new startup that aims to rival companies like Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project in technology legend, is a company based on Berners-Lee's open source platform Solid.
Solid allows users to determine where the data will be stored and which people have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokingly said that Inrupt's original intention was "to dominate the world".
"We had to do this now," Lee said about the startup.
"This is a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology, which allows users to create their own "personal online data storage space" or otherwise, POD.
This storage space can include contact lists, calendar, to-do lists, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
The app offers an experience similar to using Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify from a single browser at the same time.
The unique feature that separates personal data storage space from other technologies is that it allows the user to fully control who can access what information.
The company calls this concept "personal empowerment through data".
According to John Bruce, the company's CEO, the main idea in the creation of the Inrupt company was to bring together the resources, operations, and appropriate skills to help bring Solid to the public use.
The company currently has a security platform acquired by Berners-Lee, Bruce, IBM, a community of developers and volunteer coders working on the project on contract.
Starting this week, technology developers from all over the world can develop their own decentralized applications by taking advantage of the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he or his team "didn't discuss with Facebook and Google whether to make a change that would upset all business models overnight."
"We don't ask permission from them," Lee said.
In a post published in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee explained Inrupt's mission: "Provide commercial energy and ecosystem to help maintain the integrity and quality of the new web system built on the Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee radically changed the Internet by founding the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been one of the prominent figures in the network neutrality debate.
Berners-Lee, who started Inrupt, will continue to be the Founder and Director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation, and the Open Data Institute.
"I am very optimistic about this new era of the Web," Berners-Lee said.
