On 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann had his battalion "in very foggy weather, under the bullet rain of artillery and machine guns" pass the Saint-Quentin Canal, according to a report in the London Gazette.
Then he quickly ran towards the line of fire, "with great courage" pulling forward the line of fire, and walking alone on top of a field ball, he knocked down three of the platoonmen.
Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, a month after the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, commented on his grandfather's actions, "a heroism that I know I'll never reach, but also makes you humble."
Michael and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also left a wreath after a parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
