National Trust association overhears bats' secret lives
A new study is being conducted in a field in Highlands, Scotland, to figure out how bats benefited from the terrain during hunting.
It is hoped that the findings from the study will shed light on the behavior of bats, the only mammal to fly, and guide future conservation work.
The study, carried out by scientists at Scotland's National Trust for Scotland association, will follow the common dwarf bats and Mediterranean dwarf bats found at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross, as well as brown long-eared bats and Daubenton bats.
During the season, special recording devices will be placed at key points of the terrain to track the activities of bats.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also carry out mobile work using hand-held detectors.
Once all the recordings have been performed by experts, the frequencies of bat sounds will be determined to determine which species is doing what.
A habitat map and report will then be prepared to create a detailed picture of the behavior of bats across the land.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are more important to bats, and how these areas are used by each species of bat.
This information will benefit habitat management studies, such as grassland creation, as well as help determine how best wooded areas can be protected for bats and related species.
In the past century, there has been a significant decrease in bat population in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom.
Bats are threatened by building and building jobs that affect their perch and cause them to lose their habitat.
Other factors that pose a risk to bats include wind turbines, lighting tools, flyflies, chemical processes used in some building materials, and home cats' attacks.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey because of their hunting habits at night.
Bats are using an advanced echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles in their flight paths.
The NTS, responsible for the protection of 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, places great emphasis on bats.
The association employs ten trained experts who regularly conduct research, perch reviews, and sometimes rescue activities on the subject.
The organization established Scotland's first and only bat-specific shelter on the Threave land of Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten different bat species.
David Thompson, the land manager, stated that the land was an ideal area for bats.
"We have a great space for bats in Threeave," Thompson said.
Land manager Thompson said: "We have old buildings, lots of old trees, and a nice living space.
But we still don't know much about bats, so the work we do here and in other areas will help us understand what bats need to thrive."
Thompson underscores the need to check if there are bats in buildings before they begin maintenance work, an accidental destruction of a single mother's perch could cause the death of close to 400 females and young bats, leading to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected animals that are forbidden to kill, disturb or harm or destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust association, invited people to contribute to the project.
"We still have a lot to learn about bats, and we don't know what the populations of many species living in our region are like," Ferrell said in a statement.
