Red tide news: Groups in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota shrink
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general decline in the Red tide groups in some parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions for improper proliferation are being reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier regions, which explain the shrinking groups.
During a period of proliferation, the Red Tide expands from North Pinellas to the South Lee region by about 130 miles.
Smaller groups can be found within 10 miles of Hillsborough District, but they are less numerous than last week.
The Red tide was also observed in the Pasco Region.
Over the past week, medium-sized groups have been observed on the coast and off the coast of the Pinellas Region, small and large groups off the coast and off the Hillsborough Region, certain vague and large groups on the Manatee Region, certain uncertain and large groups on the coast and off the coast of the Sarasota Region, certain uncertain and medium-sized groups on the Charlotte Region, certain uncertain and large groups on the coast and off the Lee Region, and small groups on the Collier Region.
Respiratory disturbances continue to be reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier areas.
No reports of respiratory distress have been reported from Northwest Florida in the past week.
